  "text": "Firefox's multi-process (Fission) architecture manages content process lifecycle through several key classes in the dom/ipc/ directory:\n\n1. **ContentParent** (dom/ipc/ContentParent.h/.cpp): The parent-side actor that represents a single content process. This is the main class for managing a content process's lifecycle, including creation, communication with child processes, and cleanup during shutdown. ContentParent inherits from PContentParent and implements multiple interfaces including nsIDOMProcessParent and nsIObserver.\n\n2. **ContentProcessManager** (dom/ipc/ContentProcessManager.h/.cpp): A singleton registry that maintains a mapping of all active ContentParent instances. It provides methods to add/remove content processes, retrieve processes by ID, and manage the relationship between content processes and tabs (BrowserParent instances).\n\n3. **BrowserParent** (dom/ipc/BrowserParent.h/.cpp): The parent-side actor representing a single tab/browser instance within a content process. Each BrowserParent maintains a reference to its parent ContentParent and is managed by ContentProcessManager. This class handles tab-specific IPC communication and lifecycle.\n\n4. **PreallocatedProcessManager** (dom/ipc/PreallocatedProcessManager.h/.cpp): A manager that maintains a pool of preallocated ContentParent processes to reduce startup latency. It creates processes ahead of time based on the dom.ipc.processPrelaunch.enabled preference, allowing faster process reuse when new tabs or content is needed.\n\nThese classes work together in the content process lifecycle: ContentProcessManager tracks all ContentParent instances, which manage their child processes and associated BrowserParent tabs. PreallocatedProcessManager optimizes this by maintaining a ready-to-use process pool."
}

